This dashboard is a visualisation of a food demand survey of over 5000 participants in the US. It contained questions about weekly grocery expenditure, weekly eating our expenditure, grocery shopping challenges and priorities, household income, race, state of residence, marital status, highest education received, farming experience, food stamps, number in household, age, and several other descriptors. 

Dropping columns like race, state, and political inclination due to some groups dominating the dataset, principal component analysis was performed to send the data into a k-means clustering algorithm. We created 8 clusters out of the survey participants. 

Grocery stores can use similar techniques to identify the composition of the region they are situated in and also their customer base. This helps them target their services towards the appropriate clusters to avoid losing business. This model thus serves as a churn analysis tool.

This can also be used to identify vulnerable populations in a region and their issues.

1. Based on household income we can see that clusters 1, 2, 4, 6, and 7 are vulnerable populations. Their incomes lie between $20,000-$59000 per annum.


2. In their priorities for food shopping, finding affordable food remains on top, and grocery stores might lose these customers if prices rise.


3. Avoiding food that contains certain nutrients like carbs, trans-fats or avoiding food that might have harmful substances like pesticides, hormones are not their top priorities and hence, they do not tend to be brand conscious. 


4. If finding time to cook is a top challenge, it will become less of a problem for people who are now working from home. However for people who continue to work, and have schedules that are more hectic due to the pandemic, this will become a bigger challenge, and hence readymade food is a necessity.


5. Hence grocery stores must have abundant stocks of affordable food to cater to this population and they will not lose these customers if there are sufficient stocks. 



Cluster 1- Remains the most vulnerable with very low annual income. However, they belong to the older age group and hence are more vulnerable to the effects of the virus. Though their top priority remains to find affordable food, it is necessary for grocery stores to maintain stocks of healthy and safe food that can ensure these populations do not go undernourished during a time when they are most susceptible to disease. Eating out is not frequent and hence demand for groceries to cook food remains the same.


Cluster 2- This involves middle aged parents with 2 children, mostly below the age of 12. Their incomes are average and their main concern remains finding affordable food and something their kids will eat. Finding nutritious and food without added chemicals is the least of their concerns. They also spend a significant amount eating out and if restaurants close or as concerns about eating out rise, they will tend to spend more money on groceries and stores need to be well equipped to handle more demand. Small children are also more prone to getting infected and hence it is necessary that grocery stores keep stores of healthy foods but also food kids will eat.  


Cluster 4 and 7 are similar with finding affordable food being second priority and the difference being age group and that cluster 7 consists of younger married couples in a household. Both clusters do not have kids in the house. Again, finding affordable food is a priority, and finding items that can be used to make quick, convenient meals is a priority for cluster 7, which could be due to job schedules, which might have changed towards both extremes with the pandemic as mentioned. 


Cluster 6- This is a cluster with couples in their late forties to late sixties. They are similar to cluster 1, but finding affordable food is a third priority due to slightly higher income. Their top priorities remain eating healthy, and finding foods without chemicals and pesticides. They are likely to stop buying at a place that does not have stocks of healthy food despite it being affordable. Being from an older age group also means that it is necessary for them to keep themselves nourished during this time. These might be the customers who grocery stores lose due to non availability of different brands.

1. Clusters 0, 3, and 5 have higher household incomes and spending higher when it comes to getting the food they want is something that they are more likely to do. Their household incomes range from $80,000- $139,000 per annum. 


2. The lower age group clusters like 3 and 5 also spend a significant amount on eating out as well. They also have kids below the age of 12 in the house. While there does seem to be higher likelihood that these families might try to avoid eating out with the onset of a pandemic and spend more buying at grocery stores, they are also likely to stop buying at places that do not have stocks of food of certain brands they are used to buying.

While cluster 5 has a slightly lower income than cluster 3, their top priorities remain finding food for their kids and finding time to cook. Depending on their work schedules due to the pandemic, these priorities may change.  

Cluster 5 is also a currently farming group and also receives food stamps and hence will have money to ensure monthly nutrition.


3. Cluster 0 consists of older couples who spend slightly lesser eating out. Their top priorities remain avoiding harmful nutrients and chemicals, losing weight. Their lowest priorities are finding affordable food and finding food children will eat (no children in the house).

Due to no income constraints, they are likely to stop buying at places that do not give them the brand or type of products they want. These are the type of customers grocery stores are most likely to lose due to non availability of goods.

Thus it is important for grocery stores to identify which clusters form the majority of their customer base and target their products towards them to avoid customer churn. They can also identify the clusters that mostly make up the area or region their store is present in, and revamp their sales strategies to cater to these clusters. 


This map enables us to identify the composition of states based on the descriptors of each cluster which can be chosen under filters.

There is also a strong relationship between grocery mobility on a particular day with number of cases reported. When the number of people affected increases on a particular day, people are more afraid to step out and hence grocery stores lose customers. When the number of cases decrease, people go back to shopping. Grocery stores, especially in hard hit areas must be ready to cope with lower mobility with home delivery options to avoid losing customers to ecommerce. Local stores have the advantage of faster delivery when compared to e-commerce platforms and must make use of this advantage to retain, and also increase customer base.
